================================================================================
AMPS Earth -- GRIDLESS energetic-particle tools
================================================================================

This directory contains the gridless geospace energetic-particle solvers used by
`srcEarth/main.cpp` when the executable is launched with:

  ./amps -mode gridless -i AMPS_PARAM.in [options]

The gridless path evaluates the magnetic field directly (rather than interpolating
from a precomputed 3-D mesh) and integrates particle trajectories on the fly.
At present the gridless workflow supports two science targets:

  1) CUTOFF_RIGIDITY
     Directional / effective geomagnetic cutoff rigidity at user-selected
     locations or shell grids.

  2) DENSITY_SPECTRUM
     Local transmissivity, local spectrum, number density, and integral fluxes
     implied by a prescribed outer-boundary spectrum.

The gridless branch is intended for fast physics studies, algorithm development,
benchmarking, and eventual user-facing Runs-on-Request style workflows where the
inputs are specified in an AMPS parameter file.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. What “gridless” means here
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

“Gridless” means that the solver does NOT construct or sample a volume mesh of B
(and, in this branch, no electric field is used in the trajectory advance).
Instead, each trajectory step evaluates the magnetic field directly from the
selected field model and current particle position.

In practical terms this means:

  - no interpolation error from a precomputed field grid;
  - no mesh generation cost for the magnetic field;
  - trajectory cost is concentrated only where the solver actually traces;
  - the code is naturally suited to point, shell, and trajectory-style products.

The current gridless implementation is a magnetic-access / backtracing solver.
It is NOT a full self-consistent radiation-belt transport model and it does NOT
currently include electric-field drifts, diffusion, collisions, or wave-particle
scattering in the shared gridless backtracer.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. High-level physics model
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2.1 Backtracing principle
-------------------------

A particle observed at a location x0 inside the magnetosphere is considered
ALLOWED if the time-reversed trajectory launched from x0 escapes through the
outer domain boundary before intersecting the inner loss sphere. Otherwise it is
considered FORBIDDEN.

This is the same “allowed vs forbidden” classifier used by both major gridless
products in this directory:

  - cutoff rigidity;
  - density / spectrum / integral flux.

Keeping a shared classifier is intentional: both science products must use the
same field model, same geometry, same time stepping, and same stopping rules.


2.2 Cutoff rigidity mode
------------------------

For each observation point and each tested arrival direction, the solver searches
for the transition rigidity between forbidden and allowed access. In the gridless
implementation this is done numerically by repeated trajectory classification over
an interval specified in the input file.

Conceptually:

  Rc(x0, direction) = minimum rigidity at which the direction becomes allowed.

Depending on the configured sampling mode, the code can report either:

  - VERTICAL cutoff (single local vertical direction), or
  - an isotropic/effective cutoff based on a sampled sky of directions.

An optional directional cutoff map can also be produced in POINTS mode.


2.3 Density / spectrum mode
---------------------------

For each observation point x0 and kinetic energy E, the solver samples a set of
arrival directions and computes the allowed fraction (transmissivity):

  T(E; x0) ~= N_allowed / N_dirs

for the isotropic boundary case.

The local spectrum is then modeled as

  J_loc(E; x0) = T(E; x0) * J_b(E)

where J_b(E) is the user-provided outer-boundary differential intensity from the
#SPECTRUM section.

The total number density is obtained from

  n_tot(x0) = 4*pi * integral[ J_loc(E; x0) / v(E) ] dE

and the omnidirectional integral flux is

  F_tot(x0) = 4*pi * integral[ J_loc(E; x0) ] dE

Additional user-defined energy channels may also be integrated.


2.4 Optional anisotropic boundary mode
--------------------------------------

Density/spectrum mode supports two boundary models:

  DS_BOUNDARY_MODE = ISOTROPIC
  DS_BOUNDARY_MODE = ANISOTROPIC

In the anisotropic mode, the boundary spectrum is represented in factored form:

  J_b(E, dir, x_exit) ~= J_b_iso(E) * f_PAD(cos alpha) * f_spatial(x_exit)

where:

  - cos alpha is evaluated at the outer-boundary exit point of an allowed
    backtraced trajectory,
  - f_PAD is a pitch-angle-distribution weight,
  - f_spatial is a spatial weight on the boundary.

Supported PAD / spatial forms are implemented in:

  gridless/AnisotropicSpectrum.h
  gridless/AnisotropicSpectrum.cpp

This branch is still intentionally simple but already useful for SEP-like
field-aligned streaming, pancake-like distributions, and crude dayside/nightside
asymmetry tests.

